GONOCOCCAL DISEASE - AUSTRALIA: (NEW SOUTH WALES) INCREASED INCIDENCE
*********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 18 Jun 2014
Source: The Telegraph, Wentworth Courier report [edited]
http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/city-east/sydneys-swank-eastern-suburbs-post-a-triple-figure-increase-in-reported-cases-of-gonorrhoea/story-fngr8h22-1226958657872


[Sydney's] eastern suburbs [New South Wales state] has a reputation for bronzed bodies, activated almonds and fitness fanatics, but a health report released [in early June 2014] has diagnosed the region with some serious health black spots.

One of the most startling is a 290 per cent increase in the number of gonorrhoea notifications recorded in the 4 years between 2008 and 2012. The results were revealed as part of a comprehensive health needs assessment report released by Eastern Sydney Medicare Local (ESML). The local government area that recorded the highest increase of "The Clap" was the wealthy enclave of Woollahra.

ESML chair Tim Smyth said despite the triple figure increase residents should not be alarmed. "Look, there's not a huge epidemic out there," Dr Smyth said. "I think that the (higher) figure is probably because of a combination of better screening, better awareness and also some social changes. One of those is younger people becoming more sexually active at a younger age."

A 14 per cent year-on-year increase in chlamydia notifications was also noted. Half of these cases were recorded within the City of Sydney.

Dr Smyth said the report, released earlier this month [June 2014], was a timely reminder that sexually transmitted disease was still present in the community, particularly among those aged between 30 and 35.

Gonorrhoea is a serious infection of the genital tract in both men and women, caused by a bacterium [_Neisseria gonorrhoeae_]. It is transmitted sexually, by oral, anal or genital sex. Symptoms include [urethral] discharge or a burning sensation [on urination]. The infection is treated with a simple course of antibiotics. Left untreated, the infection can cause scarring of the fallopian tubes, ectopic (tubal) pregnancy or eventual infertility in women.

[Byline: Jessica Clement]

